INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (144, 206, 78, 8, 'Chris Robles is a solid HVAC Installer candidate with approximately 2.5 years of direct installation experience and formal trade school training. He demonstrates hands-on competency in residential HVAC installation, including ductwork, refrigerant handling, brazing, and system testing. His progression from helper to full installer shows career commitment, though he would benefit from additional certifications and more detailed documentation of commercial experience.', 80, '["HVAC system installation (residential)","Ductwork installation and fabrication","Refrigerant line installation and brazing with nitrogen","Pressure testing and vacuum pulling","Electrical wiring (thermostats, disconnect boxes)","System start-up and testing (checking pressures, subcool, superheat)","Refrigerant charging","Split-system HVAC systems","Heat pump systems","Ductless mini-split systems","Manifold gauge sets","Vacuum pumps","Hand tools proficiency","Tubing cutters and swaging tools","Customer service skills"]', '["Blueprint/schematic reading ability (not mentioned)","Commercial HVAC installation experience","Gas furnace installation and piping","Load calculation knowledge","Sheet metal fabrication skills","Advanced electrical troubleshooting","Building codes knowledge","Zoning systems experience"]', 'Chris demonstrates strong foundational installation skills with excellent hands-on experience in residential systems. His technical descriptions show he understands proper procedures (nitrogen purge during brazing, vacuum pulling, subcool/superheat checking). However, the resume lacks mention of blueprint reading, commercial experience, and gas line work. The skills list is comprehensive but could benefit from organizing by proficiency level. His progression from helper to lead installer in under a year at his first company shows strong learning capability.', 65, '["EPA Universal Certification","EPA Type I (listed separately, likely redundant with Universal)","Driver''s License","Trade School Diploma - HVAC (Southern Careers Institute)","CPR and First Aid (from previous role, may be expired)"]', '["OSHA 10 or OSHA 30 Construction Safety","NATE Installation Certification","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","Texas TDLR HVAC Technician License (if applicable)","Refrigeration Service Engineers Society (RSES) certification","Forklift certification (useful for warehouse/equipment handling)","Low voltage/thermostat wiring certification"]', 'Chris has the essential EPA Universal certification, which is critical for refrigerant handling. However, for a candidate with 2.5 years of experience, the certification portfolio is thin. OSHA safety certification is notably absent and should be a priority. NATE certification would significantly strengthen his credibility and marketability. Manufacturer certifications would demonstrate commitment to professional development. The CPR/First Aid from his lifeguard days should be updated or removed if expired.', 82, 2.5, '["Current HVAC Installer role at McCullough Heating & Air (June 2024-Present): 7+ months of full installation responsibility including complete system changeouts, ductwork, electrical, refrigerant work, and customer interaction","HVAC Installer at Strategic Heating & Air (March 2023-June 2024): 15 months performing full installations with some maintenance duties, demonstrating versatility","HVAC Installer Helper at Garner Heating & Air (June 2020-October 2020): 4 months of foundational experience learning installation basics","Home Appliance Technician at BSH (February 2020-February 2022): 2 years of relevant troubleshooting, customer service, route planning, and technical repair work that translates well to HVAC","Warehouse Associate experience: Relevant for understanding equipment handling, inventory management, and logistics"]', 'Chris has solid, progressive HVAC installation experience totaling approximately 2.5 years of direct installation work (including helper time). His career trajectory shows intentional movement toward HVAC, starting with trade school in 2019, helper position in 2020, and advancing to full installer roles. The appliance technician experience adds valuable troubleshooting and customer service skills. However, there''s a gap in his resume (October 2020-February 2022) where he returned to appliance work rather than continuing in HVACâ€”this should be addressed in interviews. His current tenure at McCullough is relatively short (7 months), and the previous role lasted only 15 months, which may raise retention concerns. The experience descriptions are detailed and demonstrate genuine hands-on work, not just assisting.', 72, '["Clear, chronological format that''s easy to follow","Detailed bullet points that demonstrate actual hands-on work rather than generic duties","Comprehensive skills section with specific tools and equipment","Good use of technical terminology (subcool, nitrogen purge, brazing, vacuum pulling)","Includes relevant education and certifications section","Contact information clearly presented","Shows career progression from helper to installer"]', '["Inconsistent capitalization (e.g., ''duck board'' should be ''duct board'', ''Preforming'' should be ''Performing'')","Some redundancy between job descriptions (could consolidate similar duties)","Professional summary is generic and doesn''t highlight HVAC expertise","Missing quantifiable achievements (number of systems installed, customer satisfaction ratings, efficiency metrics)","Skills section is disorganizedâ€”should group by category (Technical Skills, Tools, Certifications)","No mention of types of systems installed (tonnage range, system types, residential vs. commercial)","Older, less relevant jobs (Target, YMCA) take up valuable spaceâ€”could be condensed","Email address uses Indeed''s anonymous email, which is fine but a professional personal email would be better for direct applications"]', 'The resume is functional and demonstrates real experience, but it needs polish to stand out in a competitive market. The technical details are strong, which is excellent, but spelling errors (''duck board,'' ''Preforming'') undermine professionalism. The professional summary should be rewritten to emphasize ''2+ years HVAC installation experience with EPA certification'' rather than generic ''labor and driving experience.'' Adding metrics (e.g., ''Complete 3-5 residential system installations per week'' or ''Maintained 95% customer satisfaction rating'') would significantly strengthen the resume. The format is clean but could benefit from better visual hierarchy and consolidation of older, non-HVAC roles.', '["Solid hands-on installation experience with progressive responsibility from helper to lead installer","EPA Universal Certification demonstrates commitment to proper refrigerant handling and environmental compliance","Comprehensive technical skill set including brazing, pressure testing, vacuum pulling, and system chargingâ€”shows proper installation procedures","Formal HVAC trade school education provides theoretical foundation to complement hands-on experience","Strong customer service background from multiple roles, important for residential installation work","Demonstrates reliability and work ethic through multiple long-term positions (6 years at Target, 4+ years at YMCA)","Willing to relocate, which increases employment flexibility","Previous appliance technician experience shows troubleshooting ability and technical aptitude"]', '["Limited certification portfolio beyond EPAâ€”lacks OSHA safety training, NATE certification, and manufacturer certifications","Short tenure at recent HVAC positions (7 months current, 15 months previous) may indicate retention risk or job-hopping","No documented commercial HVAC installation experienceâ€”appears limited to residential work","Missing key skills documentation: blueprint reading, load calculations, gas line installation, and building codes knowledge","Resume contains spelling and grammatical errors that undermine professionalism (''duck board,'' ''Preforming'')","Lack of quantifiable achievements or metrics to demonstrate productivity and quality","Gap in HVAC career progression (returned to appliance work in 2020-2022 after helper position)","No mention of specialized systems (geothermal, high-efficiency, smart home integration, zoning systems)"]', '["Obtain OSHA 10 or OSHA 30 certification immediatelyâ€”this is a critical safety credential that many employers require and demonstrates commitment to workplace safety","Pursue NATE Installation certification within the next 6-12 months to validate skills and increase marketability and earning potential","Rewrite professional summary to lead with HVAC expertise: ''EPA-certified HVAC Installer with 2+ years of residential installation experience specializing in complete system changeouts, ductwork fabrication, and refrigerant systems''","Add quantifiable metrics to work experience: number of installations completed, customer satisfaction scores, efficiency ratings, or safety record","Proofread carefully and correct all spelling/grammar errorsâ€”consider having someone review it or use professional resume services","Seek manufacturer training and certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, Rheem) to demonstrate product expertise and increase value to employers","Gain commercial installation experience if possible, or document any commercial work already performed","Condense or remove older non-HVAC positions (Target, YMCA) to one-line entries to make room for more HVAC-specific details","Add a ''Key Qualifications'' or ''Technical Proficiencies'' section highlighting: EPA Universal Certified, 100+ residential installations completed, proficient in all major brands, etc.","Be prepared to address job tenure concerns in interviewsâ€”develop a clear narrative about career progression and commitment to current employer"]', 'YES', '2025-12-17 00:35:16', '2025-12-17 00:35:16') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (145, 207, 68, 7, 'Alexander is a recent HVAC graduate (2025) with strong certifications (EPA 608 Universal, NATE, R410A) but limited hands-on service technician experience. His HVAC experience consists primarily of UTI training and only 1 month in his current maintenance technician role (May 2025-Present). His previous 7+ years of experience is in construction/drywall work, not HVAC service. The resume is well-formatted with comprehensive certifications, but he falls into the ''NOT CLOSE TO REQUIRED'' experience tier with less than 1 year of actual HVAC field experience.', 65, '["Air Conditioning and Heating Systems","Basic and Commercial Refrigeration","Heat Pumps and Ductless Systems","Gas and Hydronic Heating Systems","Indoor Air and Ductwork fabrication","AC and DC circuits and components","Mechanical and Electronic Controls","Building Management Systems","Schematics use and Interpretation","Technical troubleshooting","Equipment maintenance","HVAC installation experience (training)","Piping and fitting basics"]', '["Actual field service experience with diagnostics","Customer service/client interaction experience","Service call completion metrics","Specific equipment brands/manufacturers","Preventative maintenance program experience","Commercial HVAC service experience"]', 'Strong theoretical foundation from UTI training with comprehensive knowledge of HVAC systems. However, lacks documented hands-on service technician experience. Skills listed are primarily educational/training-based rather than field-proven. Current maintenance role is too recent (1 month) to demonstrate practical application of skills.', 95, '["EPA 608 Universal Certification","NATE HVAC Certification","R410A Certification","OSHA 10 Certification","UTI SOC/Directors Honors"]', '["State-specific HVAC license (if required in Texas)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","HVAC Excellence certifications","Additional refrigerant handling certifications"]', 'Excellent certification portfolio for an entry-level technician. EPA 608 Universal and NATE certifications are industry-standard and highly valued. OSHA 10 shows safety awareness. The certifications demonstrate commitment to the field and strong foundational knowledge, which is a significant strength despite limited field experience.', 35, 0.08, '["G&B Property Management - Maintenance Technician (May 2025-Present): ~1 month - includes HVAC maintenance responsibilities","UTI Hands-on Technical Training (2025): Educational/training experience, not field service","Baker Triangle (April 2024-May 2025): 13 months - General maintenance, not HVAC-specific","Millard Drywall (Jan 2018-April 2024): 6+ years - Construction/drywall, not HVAC"]', 'Critical weakness: Only approximately 1 month of actual HVAC-related field experience in current maintenance role. This falls significantly short of the 2-year requirement (only 4% of required experience). Previous 7+ years of construction experience shows strong work ethic and hands-on skills but is not HVAC service work. Recent career transition into HVAC field. No work gaps detected - continuous employment history. Not job hoppy - shows stability with 6+ years at Millard Drywall. However, the lack of actual service technician experience is the primary concern.', 80, '["Clean, professional formatting with clear sections","Comprehensive qualifications and certifications section prominently displayed","Detailed bullet points describing responsibilities","Good use of technical terminology","Contact information clearly presented","Chronological work history with dates"]', '["Current role (May 2025-Present) needs more HVAC-specific accomplishments","Could better highlight HVAC-specific tasks in maintenance role","Some bullets are generic and could be more results-oriented","Could add metrics or quantifiable achievements","Education section could include GPA or honors from UTI program"]', 'Well-organized resume with professional presentation. No significant typos or grammatical errors. Good structure with clear sections. The extensive skills list effectively showcases technical knowledge. However, the resume would benefit from more emphasis on actual HVAC service work versus construction/maintenance tasks.', '["Excellent certification portfolio (EPA 608 Universal, NATE, R410A, OSHA 10) - demonstrates commitment and foundational knowledge","Recent formal HVAC training from UTI with honors recognition shows strong academic performance","Stable work history with 6+ years at previous employer - demonstrates reliability and low turnover risk","Strong hands-on construction background provides transferable skills (blueprint reading, troubleshooting, tool proficiency)","Currently employed in maintenance role with HVAC responsibilities - actively building relevant experience","Local to Austin, TX - no relocation concerns"]', '["Severely lacks required experience: only ~1 month of HVAC field work versus 2 years required (96% short of requirement)","No documented service technician experience - current role is general maintenance, not dedicated HVAC service","Cannot demonstrate customer service skills or service call completion in HVAC context","No proven track record of independent HVAC diagnostics and repairs in the field","Recent career changer - HVAC is a new field as of 2024/2025, creating uncertainty about long-term commitment"]', '["Gain at least 1-2 years of dedicated HVAC service technician experience before applying for positions requiring 2+ years","Seek mentorship or apprenticeship opportunities to build hands-on diagnostic and repair skills","Document specific HVAC service accomplishments in current role (number of service calls, types of systems serviced, customer satisfaction)","Pursue manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox) to enhance marketability","Consider applying for entry-level or apprentice HVAC service positions that don''t require 2 years of experience","Add quantifiable metrics to resume (e.g., ''Completed X service calls per week,'' ''Maintained X% customer satisfaction rating'')"]', 'MAYBE', '2025-12-18 00:23:18', '2025-12-18 00:23:18') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (146, 209, 32, 3, 'Dennis is currently an HVAC student with zero professional HVAC service technician experience, placing him in the ''NOT CLOSE TO REQUIRED'' tier (requires 2 years, has 0 years). His resume is well-formatted with clear sections and no major errors (Good Resume quality), but he has no HVAC certifications yet and his only work experience is as an in-store shopper at H-E-B. While he shows strong work ethic and is pursuing the right educational path, he does not meet the minimum experience requirement for this Service Technician position.', 15, '["Mechanical aptitude (mentioned in skills)","Technical learning (HVAC studies in progress)","Time management","Attention to detail"]', '["HVAC system diagnostics","Refrigeration cycle knowledge","Electrical troubleshooting","Ductwork installation/repair","System installation experience","Preventive maintenance procedures","Customer service in HVAC context","Tool proficiency (gauges, multimeters, etc.)","Blueprint reading","Load calculations"]', 'Dennis has no hands-on HVAC technical skills yet. While he mentions ''mechanical aptitude'' and is currently studying HVAC at ACC, he has not applied any technical HVAC knowledge in a professional setting. His current skill set is entirely retail/customer service focused. He will need to complete his training program and gain field experience before developing the technical competencies required for a Service Technician role.', 0, '[]', '["EPA 608 Universal Certification (required for refrigerant handling)","OSHA 10 Safety Certification","NATE Certification (after gaining experience)","Texas HVAC License (after meeting state requirements)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)"]', 'Dennis has no HVAC certifications listed. As a student expected to graduate in March 2026, he should prioritize obtaining his EPA 608 certification, which is typically required before working with refrigerants. Most HVAC programs include EPA 608 prep, so he should pursue this before graduation. OSHA 10 would also be valuable for safety awareness in the field.', 10, 0, '["HVAC Certification Program - In Progress at Austin Community College (Expected completion March 2026)","In-Store Personal Shopper at H-E-B Bee Cave (2+ years) - Non-HVAC retail experience"]', 'Dennis has ZERO years of HVAC Service Technician experience. The job requires 2 years minimum, making him significantly underqualified for this position. His only professional experience is in retail grocery (H-E-B), which provides transferable soft skills like customer service, time management, and reliability, but no technical HVAC experience. He is currently a student who won''t complete his HVAC training until March 2026. There are no work gaps (continuously employed at H-E-B), and he is not job hoppy. However, the complete lack of HVAC field experience is the critical disqualifying factor.', 75, '["Clean, professional formatting with clear sections","No spelling or grammatical errors","Appropriate use of bullet points","Contact information clearly displayed","Objective statement clearly states career goals and timeline"]', '["Resume is tailored for an apprenticeship, not a 2-year experienced technician role","Could add more detail about specific HVAC coursework completed at ACC","Skills section mixes retail skills with HVAC aspirations - could be more focused","Professional experience section only shows retail work, not HVAC field experience"]', 'The resume is well-constructed with good formatting, proper grammar, and professional presentation, qualifying it as a ''Good Resume'' by the rubric standards. However, the content clearly positions Dennis as an apprentice/student seeking entry-level opportunities, not as an experienced Service Technician. The resume honestly represents his current status but doesn''t align with the job requirements of 2 years of Service Technician experience.', '["Currently pursuing formal HVAC education at Austin Community College","Strong work ethic demonstrated by 2+ years of continuous employment at H-E-B","Excellent customer service background with proven reliability","Clear career goals and commitment to HVAC industry long-term","Professional resume presentation with no errors"]', '["Zero years of HVAC Service Technician experience (requires 2 years minimum)","No HVAC certifications (EPA 608, NATE, state license, etc.)","No hands-on field experience with HVAC systems, diagnostics, or repairs","Still 4+ months away from completing basic HVAC training program","All professional experience is in retail grocery, not technical trades"]', '["Complete HVAC certification program at ACC and obtain EPA 608 certification before graduation in March 2026","Seek an HVAC apprenticeship or helper position to gain hands-on field experience under licensed technicians","Apply for entry-level or apprentice HVAC positions rather than roles requiring 2+ years of experience","Consider part-time or internship opportunities in HVAC while completing education to build practical experience","Once graduated, focus on accumulating 2+ years of documented Service Technician experience before applying to positions with this requirement"]', 'STRONG_NO', '2025-12-18 00:23:50', '2025-12-18 00:23:50') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (147, 208, 72, 7, 'Alexander is a recently certified HVAC technician with strong foundational credentials (EPA 608 Universal, NATE, OSHA 10) and excellent transferable skills from 7+ years in construction trades. While he lacks direct HVAC installation experience in the field, his extensive background in blueprint reading, construction, and hands-on technical work, combined with his recent UTI training, positions him as a promising entry-level to junior HVAC installer candidate who can contribute immediately.', 75, '["Ductwork fabrication knowledge","Blueprint reading and interpretation","Schematics use and interpretation","AC and DC circuits and components","Mechanical and electronic controls","Piping and fitting basics","Gas and hydronic heating systems","Heat pumps and ductless systems","Hand and power tool proficiency","Metal framing construction","Building codes knowledge","R410A refrigerant certification","Air conditioning and heating systems knowledge","Basic and commercial refrigeration"]', '["Documented field installation experience (residential/commercial HVAC)","System start-up and commissioning experience","Refrigerant line brazing/soldering experience","Vacuum pump and leak detection procedures","Thermostat wiring and programming","Load calculations","Condensate drain installation","Equipment rigging and placement","Specific manufacturer system experience (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)"]', 'Alexander has excellent theoretical knowledge from his UTI training and lists comprehensive HVAC systems understanding. His construction background provides strong transferable skills in blueprint reading, metal framing, and working with building structuresâ€”all critical for HVAC installation. However, the resume lacks evidence of actual field installation experience with HVAC equipment. The technical skills section is impressive but needs to be validated with real-world application examples. His drywall and construction experience is actually a significant asset for HVAC installation work, particularly for cutting openings, running ductwork, and understanding building structures.', 95, '["EPA 608 Universal Certification (critical requirement - PASSED)","NATE HVAC Certification","OSHA 10 Certification","R410A Certification","UTI SOC/Directors Honors"]', '["OSHA 30 (upgrade from OSHA 10 for career advancement)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Rheem, etc.)","Texas TDLR HVAC Technician License (if pursuing service work)","Welding/Brazing certification documentation","NATE Installation Specialist certification (to complement existing NATE cert)","First Aid/CPR certification"]', 'Exceptional certification portfolio for an entry-level candidate. The EPA 608 Universal is the most critical certification for HVAC work and Alexander has it. The NATE certification demonstrates commitment to industry standards and professional development. OSHA 10 shows safety awareness. The R410A certification is valuable for working with modern refrigerants. The UTI honors designation indicates he was a top performer in his training program. This certification package would be competitive even against candidates with more field experience. This is the strongest aspect of his candidacy.', 60, 0.5, '["UTI hands-on technical training with HVAC systems (2025)","7+ years construction/maintenance experience with transferable skills","Blueprint reading and interpretation (critical for HVAC installation)","Metal framing and structural work (relevant for ductwork and equipment mounting)","Electrical outlet installation and panel preparation (transferable to HVAC electrical)","Roof work experience (relevant for rooftop unit installation)","Tool and equipment proficiency from construction background","Current maintenance technician role with HVAC exposure (May 2025-Present)","Experience working in teams on installation projects","Safety protocol adherence in construction environments"]', 'This is the primary gap in Alexander''s profile. He has approximately 6 months of HVAC-specific experience (UTI training + current maintenance role), but no documented standalone HVAC installation experience. However, his 7+ years in construction trades provides substantial transferable value. The drywall, framing, and general construction work demonstrates he can work in attics, crawl spaces, and challenging environmentsâ€”essential for HVAC installation. His blueprint reading skills are well-established. The current maintenance technician role (May 2025-Present) likely involves some HVAC work but this isn''t clearly detailed. For an entry-level installer position, his construction background combined with recent certification makes him viable, but he would need close supervision initially. He understands job sites, safety, and physical demands of the work.', 68, '["Comprehensive certifications section prominently displayed","Detailed technical skills list demonstrates knowledge breadth","Clear contact information","Chronological work history with specific dates","Detailed bullet points showing scope of responsibilities","Good use of action verbs and technical terminology"]', '["Resume is too long and dense (needs to be more concise for installer role)","Skills section is cluttered with three separate categories that could be consolidated","Lacks quantifiable achievements (number of installations, square footage, project sizes)","UTI ''Employment History'' section is confusingâ€”should be under Education or separate ''Training'' section","Current role (G&B Property Management) has generic bullet points without specific HVAC accomplishments","No summary/objective statement tailored to HVAC installation career goals","Excessive detail on drywall work that could be condensed","Missing key metrics: types of systems worked on, size of units, project completion times","Should emphasize HVAC-related aspects of current maintenance role more prominently"]', 'The resume demonstrates thoroughness but needs better targeting for HVAC installer positions. The certifications and technical skills are well-presented, but the experience section buries HVAC relevance under construction details. The current maintenance role should lead with HVAC-specific responsibilities. Consider adding a professional summary at the top: ''EPA-certified HVAC technician with UTI honors certification and 7+ years construction experience seeking to leverage technical training and hands-on mechanical aptitude in HVAC installation role.'' The resume would benefit from being condensed to emphasize HVAC-relevant experience while summarizing the construction background more briefly. Add specific examples from UTI training (types of systems installed, lab hours completed).', '["Outstanding certification portfolio including EPA 608 Universal and NATEâ€”exceeds entry-level requirements","Recent formal HVAC training from reputable institution (UTI) with honors recognition","Extensive construction background (7+ years) with directly transferable skills: blueprint reading, metal framing, working in challenging environments","Demonstrated safety consciousness with OSHA 10 certification and construction site experience","Strong mechanical aptitude evidenced by diverse hands-on technical work across multiple trades","Currently employed in maintenance role with HVAC exposureâ€”shows career progression toward HVAC field","Local to Austin, TXâ€”no relocation needed","Young career professional (2013 graduate) with longevity potential and recent upskilling investment"]', '["No documented standalone HVAC installation experience in residential or commercial settings","Lacks specific examples of complete system installations from start to finish","No mention of refrigerant handling experience, brazing, or pressure testing in real-world applications","Current role''s HVAC responsibilities are vaguely describedâ€”needs specific examples","Missing manufacturer-specific training or equipment experience","No customer-facing installation experience mentioned (important for residential installers)","Resume doesn''t clearly articulate career transition from construction to HVAC","Lacks quantifiable installation metrics or project completion examples"]', '["Add a professional summary targeting HVAC installation: ''EPA 608-certified HVAC technician with UTI honors certification and 7+ years construction experience. Seeking installer position to apply technical training, blueprint reading expertise, and proven mechanical aptitude. Strong safety record and team collaboration skills.''","Restructure current role (G&B Property Management) to lead with specific HVAC accomplishments: ''Assist with HVAC maintenance and repairs including [specific systems], filter changes, thermostat troubleshooting, and basic diagnostics. Support senior technicians on [X] service calls monthly.''","Create a separate ''HVAC Training & Projects'' section detailing specific systems installed during UTI program: types of units, tonnage, system configurations, lab hours completed (e.g., ''Completed 500+ hours hands-on training including installation of 15+ residential split systems, 3 commercial rooftop units, and ductless mini-splits'')","Condense construction experience to 2-3 bullet points emphasizing transferable skills: ''Seven years construction experience including blueprint interpretation, metal framing, structural modifications, and working in confined spacesâ€”directly applicable to HVAC installation environments.''","Pursue immediate field experience: Request to shadow or assist HVAC installers at current employer, volunteer for any HVAC-related work orders, or seek part-time helper position with installation company to build documented experience","Add specific technical accomplishments with metrics: ''Proficient in reading and interpreting HVAC blueprints and load calculations'' or ''Experienced with cutting and framing openings for ductwork in various building materials''","Consider adding a ''Tools & Equipment'' section listing specific HVAC installation tools you''re proficient with (manifold gauges, vacuum pumps, recovery machines, duct fabrication tools, etc.)"]', 'YES', '2025-12-18 00:24:06', '2025-12-18 00:24:06') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (148, 210, 52, 5, 'Ezekiel is a career-changer transitioning into HVAC with strong certifications (EPA 608 Universal, NATE Ready-to-Work, TDLR A/C Technician) but zero actual field experience as an HVAC Service Technician. He completed 175 hours of HVAC training in September 2025 but has only worked in industrial/warehouse roles (grinder operator, hydro blast technician, forklift operator). While his certifications are impressive and his resume is well-formatted, the complete lack of hands-on HVAC service experience places him in the ''NOT CLOSE TO REQUIRED'' tier, resulting in a yellow-tier score despite his strong presentation and credentials.', 45, '["Soldering and Brazing Techniques","Piping Materials and Fittings knowledge","Refrigerant Recovery and Charging Procedures","EPA 608 Universal certified","TDLR A/C Technician registered","Problem-solving and troubleshooting","Equipment operation and maintenance","Safety compliance (OSHA-10)"]', '["Actual field service experience","Residential/commercial HVAC system diagnostics","Heat pump troubleshooting","Ductwork installation/repair","Electrical troubleshooting for HVAC systems","Customer-facing service calls","Service ticket documentation","Preventive maintenance procedures"]', 'Ezekiel has completed formal HVAC training and possesses theoretical knowledge of core HVAC skills like brazing, refrigerant handling, and piping. However, he lacks practical field application of these skills. His industrial background shows strong mechanical aptitude, equipment operation, and safety awareness, which are transferable. The gap is in translating classroom knowledge to real-world service scenariosâ€”diagnosing failing systems, performing service calls, and working directly with HVAC equipment in residential/commercial settings.', 85, '["EPA 608 Universal","NATE Ready-to-Work Certification","TDLR A/C Technician (Registered)","OSHA-10 Certified"]', '["NATE Installation & Service certifications (beyond Ready-to-Work)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","HVAC Excellence Employment Ready certification","State-specific HVAC license (if required beyond TDLR registration)"]', 'Excellent certification portfolio for an entry-level candidate. EPA 608 Universal is essential and he has it. NATE Ready-to-Work shows commitment to the trade. TDLR registration demonstrates he''s legally able to work in Texas HVAC. OSHA-10 adds safety credibility. These certifications are exactly what employers want to see in someone transitioning into the field. Once he gains field experience, pursuing full NATE certifications and manufacturer training would be the next step.', 25, 0, '["HVAC Technician Training - 175 hours (Skillpoint Alliance, completed September 2025) - 0 years field experience","Grinder Operator/Quality Control Inspector (2020-2025) - 5 years non-HVAC","Hydro Blast Technician/Supervisor (2014-2019) - 5 years non-HVAC industrial","Scaffolding Builder/Crew Leader (2012-2014) - 2 years non-HVAC","Forklift Operator (2010-2012) - 2 years non-HVAC","Road Maintenance Crew/Groundskeeper (2007-2010) - 3 years non-HVAC"]', 'Zero years of actual HVAC Service Technician experience. Ezekiel has 17+ years of solid work history showing excellent work ethic, mechanical aptitude, and progression into supervisory roles, but none of it is HVAC-specific. His most recent role (Grinder Operator, 2020-2025) shows 5 years of stability, and his Hydro Blast Supervisor role (2014-2019) demonstrates leadership and technical competence. No work gaps detectedâ€”continuous employment throughout his career. Not job hoppyâ€”he maintains long tenures (5 years, 5 years, 2 years, 2 years, 3 years). However, for a position requiring 2 years of Service Technician experience, he falls into the ''NOT CLOSE TO REQUIRED'' category with 0 years.', 85, '["Clean, professional formatting with clear section headers","Well-organized chronological work history","Comprehensive skills section highlighting HVAC training","Substantive bullet points describing responsibilities and achievements","No spelling or grammatical errors detected","Contact information clearly displayed","Appropriate use of action verbs"]', '["Could add a ''Relevant Projects'' section to highlight hands-on HVAC training projects","Consider moving HVAC certifications higher or creating a dedicated ''Certifications'' section separate from skills","Could quantify achievements more (e.g., ''Led team of 4 across 50+ projects'')","Minor: Some equipment lists could be condensed for brevity"]', 'This is a GOOD quality resume. Professional presentation, no typos, proper grammar, and substantive content throughout. Each position has multiple detailed bullets explaining responsibilities. The formatting is clean and easy to read. The professional summary effectively communicates his career transition goals. The only minor improvement would be to make HVAC credentials even more prominent given his career change, but overall this is well-executed.', '["Excellent certification portfolio (EPA 608 Universal, NATE Ready-to-Work, TDLR registered) showing commitment to HVAC career","Strong mechanical aptitude demonstrated through 17+ years of hands-on industrial/equipment work","Proven leadership and supervisory experience (led teams, trained staff, managed projects)","Outstanding work stabilityâ€”no job hopping, long tenures at each employer, no employment gaps","Safety-conscious with OSHA-10 certification and experience working in high-risk industrial environments","Well-presented, professional resume with clear communication skills"]', '["Zero actual field experience as an HVAC Service Technicianâ€”only classroom training completed","No documented customer-facing service experience in HVAC context","Lacks practical troubleshooting experience with residential/commercial HVAC systems","Career transition means no established track record in HVAC service calls or installations","May require significant on-the-job training despite certifications","No references or documented HVAC work to verify hands-on competency"]', '["Seek entry-level HVAC positions (Helper, Apprentice, or Junior Technician) to gain the required 2 years of field experience before applying to standard Service Technician roles","Consider ride-along opportunities or internships with HVAC companies to build practical experience and references","Document any hands-on HVAC projects from training program (installations, repairs, diagnostics) in a ''Relevant Projects'' section","Pursue manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, etc.) to strengthen credentials while building experience","Emphasize transferable skills in cover letters: mechanical troubleshooting, equipment maintenance, customer service mindset, and safety compliance","Network with HVAC professionals and consider joining local trade associations to find mentorship and entry opportunities"]', 'MAYBE', '2025-12-18 00:24:31', '2025-12-18 00:24:31') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
