t certifications","Cannot assess technical competencies","Cannot evaluate work history or job stability"]', '["Submit resume content for proper evaluation","Ensure resume includes detailed work history with dates","List all HVAC-related certifications prominently","Include specific technical skills and equipment experience","Provide substantive bullet points describing service technician responsibilities and achievements"]', 'STRONG_NO (0-19)', '2025-12-18 00:24:42', '2025-12-18 00:24:42') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (150, 211, 45, 5, 'Dennis is an entry-level candidate currently pursuing HVAC certification at Austin Community College with expected completion in March 2026. While he demonstrates strong work ethic, reliability, and customer service skills from his retail experience, he lacks hands-on HVAC installation experience, technical certifications, and documented mechanical skills critical for an installer role. Best suited for an apprentice position with on-the-job training.', 25, '["Customer communication & issue resolution","Time management & multitasking","Attention to detail","Strong teamwork & reliability","Mechanical aptitude (claimed, not demonstrated)"]', '["HVAC system installation experience","Ductwork installation & fabrication","Refrigerant line installation","Electrical wiring & connections","Blueprint/schematic reading","Hand & power tool proficiency","System start-up & testing procedures","Brazing/soldering skills","Sheet metal work","Load calculations","HVAC troubleshooting","Safety protocols (OSHA, ladder safety, confined space)"]', 'The resume severely lacks technical HVAC skills documentation. While Dennis claims ''mechanical aptitude,'' there''s no evidence of hands-on mechanical work, tool usage, or technical problem-solving. For an installer position, employers need to see concrete examples of working with tools, equipment, or mechanical systems. Even automotive repair, home improvement projects, or relevant coursework details would strengthen this section. The skills listed are predominantly soft skills from retail work.', 20, '["HVAC Certification Program (In Progress - 50% complete, graduation March 2026)"]', '["EPA 608 Universal Certification (Critical - should obtain before graduation)","OSHA 10-Hour Construction Safety","First Aid/CPR","Forklift Certification (helpful for material handling)","Texas Driver''s License (if not already held)","NATE Installation Certification (after gaining experience)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)"]', 'Dennis is on the right track by pursuing formal HVAC education at ACC, but he''s still 15+ months from completion. Most critically, there''s no mention of EPA 608 certification, which is legally required to handle refrigerants and is often obtained during HVAC programs. He should prioritize getting EPA 608 Universal before graduation. OSHA 10 safety certification would also make him more employable. The lack of any completed certifications significantly limits his immediate hirability for an installer role, though it''s appropriate for an apprentice position.', 35, 0, '["Customer service skills transferable to residential service calls","Time management in fast-paced environment","Attention to detail in order fulfillment (translates to installation accuracy)","Reliability and consistent work attendance","Following systematic processes and procedures"]', 'Dennis has zero documented HVAC installation experience, which is the primary weakness for this position. His 2+ years at H-E-B demonstrates reliability, work ethic, and customer serviceâ€”all valuable in HVACâ€”but there''s no evidence of physical labor, mechanical work, construction, or technical hands-on experience. For an installer role that requires lifting equipment, working in attics/crawl spaces, using power tools, and physical stamina, the resume needs to show he can handle demanding physical work. He should highlight any relevant projects from his ACC coursework (lab work, installations practiced, systems worked on) or any side work like home repairs, automotive work, or construction. Without this, he''s only qualified for an apprentice/helper role where he''ll learn installation from the ground up.', 70, '["Clean, professional formatting with clear sections","Contact information prominently displayed","Appropriate use of bullet points for readability","Objective statement clearly communicates career goals and current status","Honest about being in-progress with training","Good grammar and spelling throughout"]', '["Missing dates on work experience (shows ''Month/Year â€“ Present'' instead of actual dates)","No mention of physical capabilities critical for installer work","Skills section too heavily weighted toward retail/customer service","Missing any coursework details or hands-on training from ACC program","No references or ''References available upon request'' statement","Could benefit from a ''Relevant Coursework'' or ''Technical Training'' section","Should quantify achievements (e.g., ''Fulfilled 50+ orders daily with 98% accuracy'')","Needs to emphasize physical stamina, ability to lift 50+ lbs, work in confined spaces"]', 'The resume is well-formatted and professional, which is a positive. However, it reads more like a retail worker''s resume than an HVAC installer candidate''s. Dennis needs to reframe his presentation to emphasize technical readiness. He should add a section detailing his ACC coursework (HVAC fundamentals, electrical theory, refrigeration principles, hands-on lab hours completed, etc.). The missing employment dates are a red flagâ€”employers will wonder why they''re omitted. He should also add a statement about physical capability since installer work is demanding. Overall, the presentation is competent but needs strategic repositioning toward the trades.', '["Actively pursuing formal HVAC education with clear completion timeline (March 2026)","Strong work ethic and reliability demonstrated through 2+ years of consistent employment","Excellent customer service skills valuable for residential installation interactions","Proven ability to follow procedures and maintain quality standards","Time management skills and ability to work efficiently under pressure","Young and trainable with genuine interest in building long-term HVAC career"]', '["Zero hands-on HVAC installation experience or documented mechanical work","No completed certifications (EPA 608, OSHA 10, or manufacturer training)","Still 15+ months away from completing HVAC program (March 2026)","No evidence of physical labor experience or capability for demanding installer work","Missing critical technical skills: tool proficiency, blueprint reading, electrical work, ductwork","Resume lacks any technical accomplishments or hands-on project examples","No demonstrated experience with construction, trades, or field work environments"]', '["Obtain EPA 608 Universal Certification immediatelyâ€”many testing centers offer it, and it''s essential for any HVAC work involving refrigerants. This single certification would significantly boost employability.","Add a ''Technical Training & Coursework'' section detailing specific classes completed at ACC, lab hours, systems worked on, and skills practiced (e.g., ''Completed 40 hours hands-on training in residential split system installation'' or ''Proficient in using manifold gauges, vacuum pumps, and recovery equipment'').","Seek part-time or weekend apprentice/helper position now while completing school. Even 6 months of field experience would dramatically improve candidacy. Many HVAC companies hire students for helper roles.","Complete OSHA 10-Hour Construction Safety certification online ($30-50, takes 1-2 days) to demonstrate safety awareness and commitment to the trade.","Revise skills section to emphasize any mechanical, technical, or physical work. Include specific tools used in ACC program, any automotive repair experience, home improvement projects, or physical activities that demonstrate stamina and capability for demanding work.","Add actual employment dates for H-E-B position and consider including any physical aspects of the job (lifting, standing for long periods, working in coolers/freezers) to show physical capability.","Request informational interviews or job shadowing opportunities with local HVAC companies to gain exposure and potentially secure an apprenticeship commitment upon graduation.","Consider adding a ''Physical Capabilities'' line stating ability to lift 75+ lbs, work in extreme temperatures, climb ladders, and work in confined spacesâ€”all critical for installer roles."]', 'MAYBE', '2025-12-18 00:25:01', '2025-12-18 00:25:01') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (151, 213, 82, 8, 'Adrian is a promising HVAC candidate with approximately 1 year of hands-on HVAC experience (December 2024-October 2025 at UT Austin), placing him in the ''Close to Required'' tier. He demonstrates strong commitment to the field with an Associate''s degree in HVAC (graduating December 2024), EPA certifications (Universal, Type I, Type II), and TDLR license. The resume is well-formatted with comprehensive detail, though the experience falls just short of the 2-year requirement. His bilingual skills, clean driving record, and diverse tool experience are additional assets.', 75, '["A/C split units","Air Handlers","Package Units","Coil washing","Capacitor testing and replacement","Contactor testing","Amperage testing (compressor, blower motor, condenser fans)","Filter replacement","Float switch testing","ECM fan motor replacement","Belt replacement on exhaust fans","Motor bearing greasing","Multimeter use","Brazing","Oxygen acetylene","Recovery machine","Vacuum pump","Refrigerant gauges","Rooftop HVAC systems","Heat pump systems","Ductless mini-split systems"]', '["Ductwork installation/repair","Thermostat troubleshooting","Refrigerant charging procedures","Gas furnace diagnostics","Advanced electrical troubleshooting","Customer service/communication in HVAC context"]', 'Adrian has developed a solid foundation of HVAC technical skills during his 1 year of hands-on experience. His knowledge spans multiple system types (split, package, rooftop, heat pumps) and he''s comfortable with essential maintenance tasks. His tool experience is comprehensive including brazing and refrigerant handling. However, he needs more experience with advanced diagnostics, system installation, and customer-facing service calls to reach full Service Technician proficiency.', 95, '["EPA Universal Certification","EPA Type I","EPA Type II","EPA 608 Technician Certification","TDLR #126947 (Texas HVAC License)","HVAC Contractor License","HVAC apprentice license"]', '["NATE certification (Service Installation or Service Technician)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","HVAC Excellence Employment Ready certification","OSHA 10 or 30 safety certification"]', 'Excellent certification portfolio for someone with 1 year of experience. Adrian has all essential EPA certifications (Universal) and proper Texas state licensing (TDLR). This demonstrates his commitment to professional development and regulatory compliance. Adding NATE and manufacturer certifications would significantly strengthen his credentials and marketability.', 75, 1, '["University of Texas at Austin - Maintenance Technician with HVAC duties (December 2024-October 2025): ~1 year of hands-on HVAC maintenance experience including split units, air handlers, package units, component testing/replacement, and preventive maintenance"]', 'Adrian has approximately 1 year of direct HVAC experience, placing him at 50% of the 2-year requirement (Close to Required tier). His experience is legitimate and well-documented with specific tasks and equipment types. Work history shows NO gaps - he maintained continuous employment through valet work (March 2022-Present) while pursuing his HVAC education and transitioning into the field. He is NOT job hoppy, showing stable employment patterns. The transition from service industry to HVAC is well-executed with educational support. He needs one more year of experience to meet the full requirement, but his trajectory is excellent.', 85, '["Professional formatting with clear sections","Comprehensive detail about HVAC tasks and equipment","Well-organized education and certifications section","Extensive skills list demonstrating breadth of knowledge","Clean layout with good use of white space","Bilingual capability clearly stated"]', '["Date inconsistency: ''December 2024-October 2025'' appears to be an error (future dates or should be 2023-2024)","Some redundancy between the two resume formats presented","Could consolidate skills section to highlight most relevant HVAC competencies","Professional summary could be more concise and achievement-focused"]', 'This is a GOOD quality resume with professional presentation and substantive content. The formatting is clean and easy to read. The candidate provides detailed descriptions of HVAC work performed, which is excellent. The main issue is the date error on the UT Austin position (December 2024-October 2025 appears to be future dates or a typo). Minor improvements in conciseness and removing redundancy would elevate this further, but overall it''s well-executed for an early-career professional.', '["Strong educational foundation with Associate''s degree in HVAC (graduating December 2024)","Complete EPA certification suite (Universal) and Texas state licensing (TDLR)","Hands-on experience with multiple HVAC system types (split, package, rooftop, heat pumps)","Bilingual (English/Spanish) - valuable for diverse customer base","Continuous employment history with no gaps - strong work ethic demonstrated through multiple jobs","Comprehensive tool experience including brazing and refrigerant handling","Clean driving record with Class C license"]', '["Only 1 year of HVAC experience vs. 2-year requirement (50% short)","Limited customer-facing service experience - mostly maintenance-focused","No NATE or manufacturer-specific certifications yet","Date error on resume creates confusion about actual experience timeline","Limited experience with advanced diagnostics and troubleshooting","No documented experience with residential service calls or customer interaction in HVAC context"]', '["Correct the date error on UT Austin position immediately - clarify if it''s 2023-2024 or 2024-2025","Pursue NATE Service Technician certification to validate skills and increase marketability","Seek opportunities for customer-facing service work to develop communication and diagnostic skills","Obtain manufacturer certifications from major brands (Carrier, Trane, Lennox) to expand expertise","Document any additional HVAC experience or projects completed during education to potentially increase total experience count","Consider positions that offer mentorship from experienced technicians to accelerate skill development"]', 'YES', '2025-12-18 00:25:20', '2025-12-18 00:25:20') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (152, 214, 72, 7, 'Ezekiel is a career-changer with excellent foundational HVAC certifications and strong transferable mechanical skills from industrial environments. While he lacks direct HVAC installation experience, his recent 175-hour training, EPA 608 Universal certification, and hands-on experience with welding, grinding, and industrial equipment demonstrate serious commitment to the field. His leadership background and safety consciousness make him a solid entry-level candidate.', 68, '["EPA 608 Universal Certification","Soldering and Brazing Techniques","Refrigerant Recovery and Charging Procedures","Knowledge of Piping Materials and Fittings","Hand and Power Tool Proficiency (grinder, sander, welding equipment)","Problem-Solving and Troubleshooting Skills","High-Pressure Equipment Operation (HydroBlast)","Metal Work Experience (carbon steel, stainless steel, aluminum)","Quality Control and Inspection Experience","Forklift and Equipment Operation"]', '["Actual HVAC System Installation Experience","Ductwork Installation and Fabrication","Electrical Wiring and Connections for HVAC","Blueprint/Schematic Reading (not explicitly mentioned)","Residential HVAC Installation Experience","System Start-up, Testing, and Commissioning","Sheet Metal Work","Specific HVAC Manufacturer Equipment Knowledge","Load Calculation Understanding"]', 'Strong foundational technical skills with excellent transferable abilities. The brazing, soldering, and refrigerant handling knowledge from training is exactly what''s needed. Metal working experience with various materials translates well to HVAC installation. However, lacks hands-on installation experience with actual HVAC systems, ductwork fabrication, and electrical connections. The quality control background is a plus for ensuring proper installations.', 85, '["EPA 608 Universal (Critical - Required)","TDLR A/C Technician Registration (Texas-specific, excellent)","OSHA-10 Certified (Safety foundation)","NATE Ready-to-Work Certification (Industry recognition)","HVAC Technician Training - 175 hours (Recent, relevant)"]', '["OSHA-30 (advancement from OSHA-10)","Manufacturer-Specific Certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","NATE Installation Certification (after gaining field experience)","Electrical/Low-Voltage Certification","Sheet Metal Certification (SMACNA)","First Aid/CPR"]', 'Exceptional certification portfolio for an entry-level installer. The EPA 608 Universal is essential and he has it. TDLR registration shows he''s serious about working in Texas HVAC. NATE Ready-to-Work demonstrates industry-recognized foundational knowledge. This certification package is actually stronger than many entry-level candidates. The recent completion of 175-hour training (September 2025) shows current, relevant education.', 55, 0, '["5 years as Grinder Operator/QC Inspector - metal work, quality standards, attention to detail","5+ years as HydroBlast Supervisor - high-pressure systems, industrial equipment, team leadership","2 years Scaffolding Builder - working at heights, confined spaces, safety protocols, physical demands","Strong mechanical aptitude across multiple industrial roles","Crew leadership and supervision experience (managed team of 4)","Experience in industrial/commercial environments (refineries, power plants)","Comfort with physically demanding work and challenging environments"]', 'Zero direct HVAC installation experience, which is the primary weakness. However, the transferable skills are substantial: metal working, industrial equipment operation, working in extreme conditions (heights, confined spaces, refineries), and physical stamina. The progression from operator to supervisor shows capability and reliability. For an entry-level installer position, this industrial background is actually valuable - he understands safety, quality standards, and working on complex systems. Most concerning is the lack of residential installation experience, as customer interaction and home environments differ significantly from industrial settings.', 78, '["Clean, professional formatting with clear section headers","Well-organized chronological work history","Strong use of action verbs and quantifiable details","Comprehensive skills section tailored to HVAC transition","Contact information clearly displayed","Good balance of technical and soft skills","Demonstrates career progression and stability"]', '["Professional summary focuses too much on warehouse/forklift work rather than HVAC transition","Some redundancy (propane tank refilling listed twice in same role)","Could add a ''Relevant Projects'' or ''Training Highlights'' section to showcase HVAC coursework","Missing specific HVAC-related accomplishments from training program","Equipment lists are somewhat scattered - could consolidate","No mention of physical capabilities (lifting capacity, comfort in attics/crawlspaces)","Could benefit from a brief objective statement specifically targeting HVAC installation"]', 'Solid resume presentation that effectively communicates work history and reliability. The format is easy to scan and professional. However, the professional summary needs revision to emphasize HVAC readiness rather than warehouse operations. Consider adding a section highlighting specific HVAC systems worked on during training, or projects completed. The skills section is strong but could be reorganized to prioritize HVAC-specific competencies first, then transferable skills.', '["Outstanding certification portfolio for entry-level (EPA 608 Universal, TDLR, NATE Ready-to-Work, OSHA-10)","Recent, relevant HVAC training (175 hours completed September 2025) shows commitment and current knowledge","Proven leadership and supervisory experience (managed teams, trained staff)","Strong safety consciousness from industrial background (refineries, high-pressure systems, confined spaces)","Excellent mechanical aptitude with hands-on experience in welding, grinding, and metal work","Demonstrated reliability and work ethic (5-year tenure at most recent position)","Comfortable with physically demanding work in challenging environments (heights, confined spaces, extreme conditions)","Quality control experience ensures attention to detail in installations","Customer service skills mentioned and likely developed through various roles"]', '["Zero direct HVAC installation experience - no hands-on system installations documented","No demonstrated experience with ductwork fabrication or installation","Limited or no electrical wiring experience for HVAC systems","No blueprint or schematic reading experience mentioned","Lack of residential installation experience (all background is industrial/commercial)","No evidence of working directly with homeowners or in residential settings","Recent career change may indicate learning curve ahead","No manufacturer-specific equipment training or certifications","Gap in demonstrating actual HVAC system start-up and commissioning experience"]', '["Revise professional summary to lead with HVAC career transition and highlight recent training and certifications rather than warehouse experience","Add a ''Relevant HVAC Training'' or ''Technical Projects'' section detailing specific systems, installations, or scenarios practiced during 175-hour training program","Seek an apprenticeship or helper position to gain supervised installation experience - emphasize willingness to start at entry level","Obtain manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Rheem) to increase marketability and demonstrate continued learning","Consider adding a brief cover letter that directly addresses the career transition and explains how industrial experience translates to HVAC installation","Pursue additional electrical/low-voltage training to strengthen weak area in HVAC electrical connections","Network with HVAC contractors and consider ride-alongs or job shadowing to gain exposure before formal employment","Emphasize physical capabilities and comfort working in attics, crawlspaces, and residential environments in interviews","Remove redundant bullet point about propane tank refilling in Starks Welding position"]', 'YES', '2025-12-18 00:25:57', '2025-12-18 00:25:57') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
