INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (154, 216, 62, 6, 'Adrian is an emerging HVAC professional with approximately 1 year of hands-on maintenance experience and strong educational credentials (Associate''s in HVAC, EPA certifications). While he demonstrates foundational knowledge in HVAC maintenance and troubleshooting, his experience is heavily weighted toward maintenance rather than installation. His bilingual skills, clean driving record, and willingness to relocate are valuable assets for an installer role.', 58, '["Split-system HVAC experience","Air handler familiarity","Package unit experience","Capacitor testing and replacement","Contactor testing","Amperage testing","ECM fan motor replacement","Multimeter proficiency","Basic hand tools (screwdrivers, ratchets, pliers, drill)","Brazing and oxygen-acetylene experience","Recovery machine operation","Vacuum pump usage","Refrigerant gauge reading","Rooftop work experience","Electrical troubleshooting basics","Power tool experience"]', '["Ductwork installation and fabrication","Refrigerant line installation (copper piping)","System start-up procedures","Blueprint/schematic reading","Load calculations","Residential/commercial new installation experience","Condensate drain installation","Thermostat wiring and programming","Equipment rigging and placement","Sheet metal work","Nitrogen pressure testing","System commissioning"]', 'Adrian has solid maintenance and troubleshooting fundamentals but lacks critical installation-specific skills. His experience is primarily component-level maintenance (coil cleaning, capacitor replacement) rather than full system installation. The brazing and recovery machine experience is positive, but he needs hands-on installation training in ductwork, refrigerant line sets, and complete system installations. His tool experience is adequate for entry-level but needs expansion into installation-specific tools.', 85, '["EPA 608 Universal Certification (Type I, II, and Universal listed)","TDLR HVAC Apprentice License #126947","Associate''s Degree in HVAC and Refrigeration (completing December 2024)","Clean Class C Driver''s License"]', '["OSHA 10 or OSHA 30 Construction Safety","NATE Installation Certification","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","Forklift/Aerial Lift certification","First Aid/CPR"]', 'Excellent certification foundation for an entry-level installer. The EPA Universal certification is essential and already obtained. The TDLR apprentice license shows commitment to the trade. Completing the Associate''s degree demonstrates theoretical knowledge. To advance, he should pursue OSHA safety training (critical for installers) and manufacturer certifications which many employers require or prefer.', 55, 1, '["1 year as Maintenance Technician at UT Austin (Dec 2024-Oct 2025) - NOTE: Future dates appear to be a typo, likely Dec 2023-Oct 2024","Hands-on work with split units, air handlers, package units, and window units","Component-level repairs and testing","Rooftop equipment access and work","Belt replacement and motor maintenance","Basic electrical testing (amperage, continuity)","Customer service experience from valet and retail positions","Self-employed lawn care business showing initiative and work ethic"]', 'Adrian has approximately 1 year of relevant HVAC experience, which meets the minimum threshold for entry-level installer positions. However, his experience is maintenance-focused rather than installation-focused. He''s worked on existing systems but hasn''t demonstrated experience installing new systems from scratch. The maintenance background is valuable for understanding system operation but doesn''t directly translate to installation skills like ductwork fabrication, line set installation, or equipment placement. His non-HVAC work history shows reliability, customer service skills, and physical capability (lawn care, delivery driving), which are transferable assets.', 45, '["Comprehensive skills list showing breadth of knowledge","Clear contact information","Certifications prominently listed","Bilingual capability highlighted","Tool experience section is helpful","Willingness to relocate clearly stated"]', '["Major date inconsistency: UT Austin position shows Dec 2024-Oct 2025 (future dates)","Redundant information - work experience section appears twice with different formatting","Skills section is excessively long and unfocused (80+ skills listed)","Lacks quantifiable achievements or metrics","Professional summary is missing - jumps directly to experience","No clear objective statement for installer role","Formatting is inconsistent between sections","Too much emphasis on non-HVAC jobs (valet, delivery, cashier)","HVAC experience description is narrative rather than bullet points with accomplishments"]', 'The resume needs significant restructuring for an installer position. The date error (future dates for UT Austin) is a red flag that suggests carelessness. The skills section is overwhelming and diluted - listing ''animal restraint'' alongside HVAC skills reduces credibility. The resume should lead with HVAC qualifications and minimize non-relevant work history. Use bullet points with action verbs and quantifiable results. The redundant work experience sections suggest this may be an Indeed-generated format that needs manual cleanup. For an installer role, emphasize hands-on technical work, physical capabilities, and any installation-related projects from school.', '["Strong educational foundation with Associate''s degree in HVAC nearing completion","EPA Universal Certification and active TDLR apprentice license demonstrate commitment and regulatory compliance","Bilingual (English/Spanish) - highly valuable in diverse customer base and work crews","Hands-on experience with multiple HVAC system types (split systems, package units, air handlers)","Demonstrated mechanical aptitude across multiple domains (HVAC, automotive, lawn equipment)","Clean driving record and willingness to relocate show reliability and flexibility","Customer service background from valet and retail positions","Self-starter mentality evidenced by lawn care business ownership"]', '["Limited installation experience - primarily maintenance and repair focused with no documented full system installations","Only 1 year of direct HVAC field experience, which is minimal for independent installer work","No demonstrated ductwork fabrication or installation experience","Missing critical installer skills: blueprint reading, load calculations, system commissioning","Lack of OSHA safety certification (essential for installation work)","Resume presentation issues: date errors, redundancy, unfocused skills section significantly undermine professionalism","No quantifiable achievements or project examples in HVAC work","Limited commercial installation exposure - experience appears residential/institutional maintenance focused"]', '["IMMEDIATELY correct the date error for UT Austin position (shows future dates Dec 2024-Oct 2025) - this is a critical credibility issue","Restructure resume to lead with HVAC qualifications: Create a strong professional summary targeting installer roles, move certifications near the top, and condense skills list to 15-20 most relevant technical skills","Obtain OSHA 10 Construction Safety certification before applying to installer positions - this is often a minimum requirement and shows safety consciousness","Seek installation-specific experience: Request to shadow or assist with installation projects at current/future employer, emphasizing new system installations rather than just maintenance","Develop and document installation competencies: Take initiative to learn ductwork fabrication, refrigerant line installation, and system start-up procedures; document any installation projects completed during apprenticeship","Add quantifiable achievements: Include metrics like ''Maintained 50+ HVAC units across campus,'' ''Reduced service callbacks by X%,'' or ''Completed X equipment replacements''","Pursue manufacturer certifications: Complete at least one major brand certification (Carrier, Trane, Lennox) to increase marketability","Create a portfolio: Document before/after photos of work, systems installed during training, and any complex repairs to demonstrate hands-on capability during interviews"]', 'MAYBE', '2025-12-18 00:27:12', '2025-12-18 00:27:12') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
