INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (156, 218, 72, 7, 'Alexander is a recently certified HVAC technician with strong foundational credentials (EPA 608 Universal, NATE, OSHA 10) and excellent transferable skills from 7+ years in construction trades. While he lacks direct HVAC installation experience in the field, his extensive background in blueprint reading, construction, and hands-on technical work, combined with his recent UTI training, positions him as a promising entry-level to junior HVAC installer candidate who can contribute immediately.', 75, '["Ductwork fabrication knowledge","Blueprint reading and interpretation","Schematics use and interpretation","AC and DC circuits and components","Mechanical and electronic controls","Piping and fitting basics","Gas and hydronic heating systems","Heat pumps and ductless systems","Hand and power tool proficiency","Metal framing construction","Building codes knowledge","R410A refrigerant certification","Air conditioning and heating systems knowledge","Basic and commercial refrigeration"]', '["Documented field installation experience (residential/commercial HVAC)","System start-up and commissioning experience","Refrigerant line brazing/soldering experience","Vacuum pump and leak detection procedures","Thermostat wiring and programming","Load calculations","Condensate drain installation","Equipment rigging and placement","Specific manufacturer system experience (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)"]', 'Alexander has excellent theoretical knowledge from his UTI training and lists comprehensive HVAC systems understanding. His construction background provides strong transferable skills in blueprint reading, metal framing, and working with building structuresâ€”all critical for HVAC installation. However, the resume lacks evidence of actual field installation experience with HVAC equipment. The technical skills section is impressive but needs to be validated with real-world application examples. His drywall and construction experience is actually a significant asset for HVAC installation work, particularly for cutting openings, running ductwork, and understanding building structures.', 95, '["EPA 608 Universal Certification (critical requirement - PASSED)","NATE HVAC Certification","OSHA 10 Certification","R410A Certification","UTI SOC/Directors Honors"]', '["OSHA 30 (upgrade from OSHA 10 for career advancement)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Rheem, etc.)","Texas TDLR HVAC Technician License (if pursuing service work)","Welding/Brazing certification documentation","NATE Installation Specialist certification (to complement existing NATE cert)","First Aid/CPR certification"]', 'Exceptional certification portfolio for an entry-level candidate. The EPA 608 Universal is the most critical certification for HVAC work and Alexander has it. The NATE certification demonstrates commitment to industry standards and professional development. OSHA 10 shows safety awareness. The R410A certification is valuable for working with modern refrigerants. The UTI honors designation indicates he was a top performer in his training program. This certification package would be competitive even against candidates with more field experience. This is the strongest aspect of his candidacy.', 60, 0.5, '["UTI hands-on technical training with HVAC systems (2025)","7+ years construction/maintenance experience with transferable skills","Blueprint reading and interpretation (critical for HVAC installation)","Metal framing and structural work (relevant for ductwork and equipment mounting)","Electrical outlet installation and panel preparation (transferable to HVAC electrical)","Roof work experience (relevant for rooftop unit installation)","Tool and equipment proficiency from construction background","Current maintenance technician role with HVAC exposure (May 2025-Present)","Experience working in teams on installation projects","Safety protocol adherence in construction environments"]', 'This is the primary gap in Alexander''s profile. He has approximately 6 months of HVAC-specific experience (UTI training + current maintenance role), but no documented standalone HVAC installation experience. However, his 7+ years in construction trades provides substantial transferable value. The drywall, framing, and general construction work demonstrates he can work in attics, crawl spaces, and challenging environmentsâ€”essential for HVAC installation. His blueprint reading skills are well-established. The current maintenance technician role (May 2025-Present) likely involves some HVAC work but this isn''t clearly detailed. For an entry-level installer position, his construction background combined with recent certification makes him viable, but he would need close supervision initially. He understands job sites, safety, and physical demands of the work.', 68, '["Comprehensive certifications section prominently displayed","Detailed technical skills list demonstrates knowledge breadth","Clear contact information","Chronological work history with specific dates","Detailed bullet points showing scope of responsibilities","Good use of action verbs and technical terminology"]', '["Resume is too long and dense (needs to be more concise for installer role)","Skills section is cluttered with three separate categories that could be consolidated","Lacks quantifiable achievements (number of installations, square footage, project sizes)","UTI ''Employment History'' section is confusingâ€”should be under Education or separate ''Training'' section","Current role (G&B Property Management) has generic bullet points without specific HVAC accomplishments","No summary/objective statement tailored to HVAC installation career goals","Excessive detail on drywall work that could be condensed","Missing key metrics: types of systems worked on, size of units, project completion times","Should emphasize HVAC-related aspects of current maintenance role more prominently"]', 'The resume demonstrates thoroughness but needs better targeting for HVAC installer positions. The certifications and technical skills are well-presented, but the experience section buries HVAC relevance under construction details. The current maintenance role should lead with HVAC-specific responsibilities. Consider adding a professional summary at the top: ''EPA-certified HVAC technician with UTI honors certification and 7+ years construction experience seeking to leverage technical training and hands-on mechanical aptitude in HVAC installation role.'' The resume would benefit from being condensed to emphasize HVAC-relevant experience while summarizing the construction background more briefly. Add specific examples from UTI training (types of systems installed, lab hours completed).', '["Outstanding certification portfolio including EPA 608 Universal and NATEâ€”exceeds entry-level requirements","Recent formal HVAC training from reputable institution (UTI) with honors recognition","Extensive construction background (7+ years) with directly transferable skills: blueprint reading, metal framing, working in challenging environments","Demonstrated safety consciousness with OSHA 10 certification and construction site experience","Strong mechanical aptitude evidenced by diverse hands-on technical work across multiple trades","Currently employed in maintenance role with HVAC exposureâ€”shows career progression toward HVAC field","Local to Austin, TXâ€”no relocation needed","Young career professional (2013 graduate) with longevity potential and recent upskilling investment"]', '["No documented standalone HVAC installation experience in residential or commercial settings","Lacks specific examples of complete system installations from start to finish","No mention of refrigerant handling experience, brazing, or pressure testing in real-world applications","Current role''s HVAC responsibilities are vaguely describedâ€”needs specific examples","Missing manufacturer-specific training or equipment experience","No customer-facing installation experience mentioned (important for residential installers)","Resume doesn''t clearly articulate career transition from construction to HVAC","Lacks quantifiable installation metrics or project completion examples"]', '["Add a professional summary targeting HVAC installation: ''EPA 608-certified HVAC technician with UTI honors certification and 7+ years construction experience. Seeking installer position to apply technical training, blueprint reading expertise, and proven mechanical aptitude. Strong safety record and team collaboration skills.''","Restructure current role (G&B Property Management) to lead with specific HVAC accomplishments: ''Assist with HVAC maintenance and repairs including [specific systems], filter changes, thermostat troubleshooting, and basic diagnostics. Support senior technicians on [X] service calls monthly.''","Create a separate ''HVAC Training & Projects'' section detailing specific systems installed during UTI program: types of units, tonnage, system configurations, lab hours completed (e.g., ''Completed 500+ hours hands-on training including installation of 15+ residential split systems, 3 commercial rooftop units, and ductless mini-splits'')","Condense construction experience to 2-3 bullet points emphasizing transferable skills: ''Seven years construction experience including blueprint interpretation, metal framing, structural modifications, and working in confined spacesâ€”directly applicable to HVAC installation environments.''","Pursue immediate field experience: Request to shadow or assist HVAC installers at current employer, volunteer for any HVAC-related work orders, or seek part-time helper position with installation company to build documented experience","Add specific technical accomplishments with metrics: ''Proficient in reading and interpreting HVAC blueprints and load calculations'' or ''Experienced with cutting and framing openings for ductwork in various building materials''","Consider adding a ''Tools & Equipment'' section listing specific HVAC installation tools you''re proficient with (manifold gauges, vacuum pumps, recovery machines, duct fabrication tools, etc.)"]', 'YES', '2025-12-18 00:35:01', '2025-12-18 00:35:01') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (157, 219, 45, 5, 'Dennis is an entry-level candidate currently pursuing HVAC certification at Austin Community College with expected completion in March 2026. While he demonstrates strong work ethic, reliability, and customer service skills from his retail experience, he lacks hands-on HVAC installation experience, technical certifications, and documented mechanical skills critical for an installer role. Best suited for an apprentice position with on-the-job training.', 25, '["Customer communication & issue resolution","Time management & multitasking","Attention to detail","Strong teamwork & reliability","Mechanical aptitude (claimed, not demonstrated)"]', '["HVAC system installation experience","Ductwork installation & fabrication","Refrigerant line installation","Electrical wiring & connections","Blueprint/schematic reading","Hand & power tool proficiency","System start-up & testing procedures","Brazing/soldering skills","Sheet metal work","Load calculations","HVAC troubleshooting","Safety protocols (OSHA, ladder safety, confined space)"]', 'The resume severely lacks technical HVAC skills documentation. While Dennis claims ''mechanical aptitude,'' there''s no evidence of hands-on mechanical work, tool usage, or technical problem-solving. For an installer position, employers need to see concrete examples of working with tools, equipment, or mechanical systems. Even automotive repair, home improvement projects, or relevant coursework details would strengthen this section. The skills listed are predominantly soft skills from retail work.', 20, '["HVAC Certification Program (In Progress - 50% complete, graduation March 2026)"]', '["EPA 608 Universal Certification (Critical - should obtain before graduation)","OSHA 10-Hour Construction Safety","First Aid/CPR","Forklift Certification (helpful for material handling)","Texas Driver''s License (if not already held)","NATE Installation Certification (after gaining experience)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)"]', 'Dennis is on the right track by pursuing formal HVAC education at ACC, but he''s still 15+ months from completion. Most critically, there''s no mention of EPA 608 certification, which is legally required to handle refrigerants and is often obtained during HVAC programs. He should prioritize getting EPA 608 Universal before graduation. OSHA 10 safety certification would also make him more employable. The lack of any completed certifications significantly limits his immediate hirability for an installer role, though it''s appropriate for an apprentice position.', 35, 0, '["Customer service skills transferable to residential service calls","Time management in fast-paced environment","Attention to detail in order fulfillment (translates to installation accuracy)","Reliability and consistent work attendance","Following systematic processes and procedures"]', 'Dennis has zero documented HVAC installation experience, which is the primary weakness for this position. His 2+ years at H-E-B demonstrates reliability, work ethic, and customer serviceâ€”all valuable in HVACâ€”but there''s no evidence of physical labor, mechanical work, construction, or technical hands-on experience. For an installer role that requires lifting equipment, working in attics/crawl spaces, using power tools, and physical stamina, the resume needs to show he can handle demanding physical work. He should highlight any relevant projects from his ACC coursework (lab work, installations practiced, systems worked on) or any side work like home repairs, automotive work, or construction. Without this, he''s only qualified for an apprentice/helper role where he''ll learn installation from the ground up.', 70, '["Clean, professional formatting with clear sections","Contact information prominently displayed","Appropriate use of bullet points for readability","Objective statement clearly communicates career goals and current status","Honest about being in-progress with training","Good grammar and spelling throughout"]', '["Missing dates on work experience (shows ''Month/Year â€“ Present'' instead of actual dates)","No mention of physical capabilities critical for installer work","Skills section too heavily weighted toward retail/customer service","Missing any coursework details or hands-on training from ACC program","No references or ''References available upon request'' statement","Could benefit from a ''Relevant Coursework'' or ''Technical Training'' section","Should quantify achievements (e.g., ''Fulfilled 50+ orders daily with 98% accuracy'')","Needs to emphasize physical stamina, ability to lift 50+ lbs, work in confined spaces"]', 'The resume is well-formatted and professional, which is a positive. However, it reads more like a retail worker''s resume than an HVAC installer candidate''s. Dennis needs to reframe his presentation to emphasize technical readiness. He should add a section detailing his ACC coursework (HVAC fundamentals, electrical theory, refrigeration principles, hands-on lab hours completed, etc.). The missing employment dates are a red flagâ€”employers will wonder why they''re omitted. He should also add a statement about physical capability since installer work is demanding. Overall, the presentation is competent but needs strategic repositioning toward the trades.', '["Actively pursuing formal HVAC education with clear completion timeline (March 2026)","Strong work ethic and reliability demonstrated through 2+ years of consistent employment","Excellent customer service skills valuable for residential installation interactions","Proven ability to follow procedures and maintain quality standards","Time management skills and ability to work efficiently under pressure","Young and trainable with genuine interest in building long-term HVAC career"]', '["Zero hands-on HVAC installation experience or documented mechanical work","No completed certifications (EPA 608, OSHA 10, etc.) - still 15 months from program completion","Lack of demonstrated technical skills with tools, equipment, or mechanical systems","No evidence of physical labor experience or capability for demanding installation work","Resume heavily skewed toward retail/customer service rather than technical trades","Missing critical details about HVAC coursework, lab hours, or practical training completed","Won''t be certification-ready until March 2026, limiting immediate contribution to installation team"]', '["Obtain EPA 608 Universal Certification immediately (can be done independently before ACC graduation) - this is non-negotiable for HVAC work and will significantly improve employability","Add detailed ''Relevant Coursework & Training'' section listing specific HVAC classes completed, lab hours, systems worked on, and skills practiced (ductwork, electrical, refrigeration, etc.)","Seek part-time apprentice or helper position now while completing education - even 6-12 months of hands-on experience before graduation would be invaluable","Complete OSHA 10-Hour Construction Safety certification to demonstrate safety awareness and make yourself more attractive to employers","Reframe existing experience to highlight transferable skills: physical aspects of retail work (lifting, standing, fast-paced environment), problem-solving, following technical procedures","Add any relevant mechanical experience, even informal (car repairs, home improvement, building projects, equipment maintenance) to demonstrate hands-on aptitude","Include statement about physical capabilities: ''Able to lift 75+ lbs, work in confined spaces, attics, and outdoor environments in all weather conditions''","Network with HVAC companies now for apprenticeship opportunities that align with school schedule - many companies value candidates in formal training programs","Consider volunteering or shadowing HVAC technicians to gain exposure and add relevant experience to resume before graduation"]', 'MAYBE', '2025-12-18 00:35:57', '2025-12-18 00:35:57') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (158, 220, 52, 5, 'Ezekiel is a career-changer transitioning into HVAC with strong certifications (EPA 608 Universal, NATE Ready-to-Work, TDLR A/C Technician) but zero actual field experience as an HVAC Service Technician. He completed 175 hours of HVAC training in September 2025 but has only worked in industrial/warehouse roles (grinder operator, hydro blast technician, forklift operator). While his mechanical aptitude, safety certifications (OSHA-10), and hands-on skills (soldering, brazing) are promising, he falls into the ''NOT CLOSE TO REQUIRED'' tier with <1 year (essentially 0 years) of Service Technician experience against a 2-year requirement.', 45, '["Soldering and Brazing Techniques","Piping Materials and Fittings knowledge","Refrigerant Recovery and Charging Procedures","EPA 608 Universal certified","NATE Ready-to-Work","TDLR A/C Technician registration","OSHA-10 safety training","Mechanical equipment operation (various tools and machinery)","Problem-solving and troubleshooting skills"]', '["Actual hands-on HVAC service experience","Residential or commercial HVAC system diagnostics","Heat pump and furnace troubleshooting","Electrical diagnostics for HVAC systems","Customer-facing service call experience","HVAC software/dispatch system familiarity","Ductwork installation or repair","Preventive maintenance protocols"]', 'Ezekiel has completed formal HVAC training and possesses foundational technical knowledge (refrigerant handling, brazing, piping). However, these are classroom/lab skills without field application. His industrial background shows strong mechanical aptitude and safety consciousness, which are transferable, but he lacks the practical service technician experience needed for independent troubleshooting and customer interaction in residential/commercial HVAC settings.', 75, '["EPA 608 Universal","NATE Ready-to-Work Certification","TDLR A/C Technician (Registered)","OSHA-10 Certified"]', '["NATE Service Technician Certification (after gaining field experience)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","Texas HVAC Contractor License (as career progresses)","Advanced electrical/controls training"]', 'Excellent certification portfolio for an entry-level candidate. EPA 608 Universal is essential and he has it. NATE Ready-to-Work shows commitment to the trade. TDLR registration demonstrates he''s legally prepared to work in Texas. OSHA-10 adds safety credibility. These certifications are the strongest aspect of his candidacy and show serious preparation for the career transition.', 25, 0, '["HVAC Technician Training - 175 hours (Skillpoint Alliance, completed Sept 2025) - 0 years field experience","Grinder Operator/QC Inspector (2020-2025) - 5 years non-HVAC industrial work","Hydro Blast Technician/Supervisor (2014-2019) - 5 years industrial cleaning, some transferable mechanical skills","Scaffolding Builder/Crew Leader (2012-2014) - 2 years construction-related","Forklift Operator (2010-2012) - 2 years warehouse","Road Maintenance/Groundskeeper (2007-2010) - 3 years municipal work"]', 'Zero years of actual HVAC Service Technician experience. While Ezekiel has 15+ years of solid work history showing reliability and mechanical aptitude, none of it is in HVAC service. His industrial background (hydro blast, welding inspection, equipment operation) demonstrates he can handle tools and follow safety protocols, but he''s essentially an entry-level HVAC candidate. No work gaps detected - continuous employment from 2007-2025 with good tenure at each position (2-5 years per employer), showing he''s not job hoppy. This is a career transition candidate who would need extensive on-the-job training.', 80, '["Clean, professional formatting with clear section headers","Well-organized chronological work history","Comprehensive skills section highlighting HVAC training","Detailed bullet points describing responsibilities at each position","No spelling errors or major grammatical issues","Contact information clearly presented"]', '["Could add a ''Relevant Projects'' section from HVAC training to showcase hands-on work","Professional summary could be more concise and HVAC-focused","Some bullets are repetitive (propane tank refilling mentioned twice for same job)","Could quantify achievements more (e.g., ''Led team of 4 across 20+ projects'')"]', 'This is a good quality resume with professional presentation. Formatting is clean, content is substantive with 4-6 bullets per position, and there are no significant typos or grammar errors. The resume effectively communicates his work history and recent HVAC training. Minor improvements could be made in eliminating redundancy and adding more HVAC-specific accomplishments from his training program.', '["Excellent certification portfolio (EPA 608 Universal, NATE Ready-to-Work, TDLR registered, OSHA-10)","Strong work ethic with 15+ years of continuous employment and no job hopping","Demonstrated mechanical aptitude through industrial equipment operation and maintenance","Leadership experience (supervised teams, trained staff, coordinated projects)","Safety-conscious with formal OSHA training and experience in high-risk environments","Recent formal HVAC training (175 hours) shows commitment to career transition"]', '["Zero actual field experience as an HVAC Service Technician (does not meet 2-year requirement)","No customer-facing residential/commercial HVAC service experience","Lacks practical diagnostic and troubleshooting experience on HVAC systems","No experience with service calls, scheduling, or customer communication in HVAC context","Would require extensive on-the-job training despite certifications","Career transition risk - unproven in HVAC field despite strong industrial background"]', '["Seek entry-level HVAC helper or apprentice positions to gain the required 2 years of field experience","Consider ride-along opportunities or internships with established HVAC companies to build practical skills","Document any hands-on projects from HVAC training program to demonstrate applied knowledge","Pursue manufacturer-specific certifications once employed to increase marketability","Emphasize transferable skills (mechanical troubleshooting, safety protocols, team leadership) in interviews","Network with HVAC professionals and join local trade associations to learn about entry-level opportunities"]', 'MAYBE', '2025-12-18 00:46:13', '2025-12-18 00:46:13') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (159, 221, 82, 8, 'Adrian is a promising HVAC candidate with approximately 1 year of hands-on HVAC experience (December 2024-October 2025 at UT Austin), placing him in the ''Close to Required'' tier. He demonstrates strong commitment to the field with an Associate''s degree in HVAC (graduating December 2024), EPA certifications (Universal, Type I, Type II), and TDLR license. The resume is well-formatted with comprehensive detail, though the experience falls just short of the 2-year requirement. His bilingual skills, clean driving record, and diverse tool experience are additional assets.', 75, '["A/C split units","Air Handlers","Package Units","Coil washing","Capacitor testing and replacement","Contactor testing","Amperage testing (compressor, blower motor, condenser fans)","Filter replacement","Float switch testing","ECM fan motor replacement","Belt replacement on exhaust fans","Motor bearing greasing","Multimeter use","Brazing","Oxygen acetylene","Recovery machine","Vacuum pump","Refrigerant gauges","Rooftop HVAC systems","Heat pump systems","Ductless mini-split systems"]', '["Ductwork installation/repair","Thermostat troubleshooting","Refrigerant charging procedures","Gas furnace diagnostics","Advanced electrical troubleshooting","Customer service/communication in HVAC context"]', 'Adrian has developed a solid foundation of HVAC technical skills during his 1 year of hands-on experience. His knowledge spans multiple system types (split, package, rooftop, heat pumps) and he''s comfortable with essential maintenance tasks. His tool experience is comprehensive including brazing and refrigerant handling. However, he needs more experience with advanced diagnostics, system installation, and customer-facing service calls to reach full Service Technician proficiency.', 95, '["EPA Universal Certification","EPA Type I","EPA Type II","EPA 608 Technician Certification","TDLR #126947 (Texas HVAC License)","HVAC Contractor License","HVAC apprentice license"]', '["NATE certification (Service Installation or Service Technician)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","HVAC Excellence Employment Ready certification","OSHA 10 or 30 safety certification"]', 'Excellent certification portfolio for someone with 1 year of experience. Adrian has all essential EPA certifications (Universal) and proper Texas state licensing (TDLR). This demonstrates his commitment to professional development and regulatory compliance. Adding NATE and manufacturer certifications would significantly strengthen his credentials and marketability.', 75, 1, '["University of Texas at Austin - Maintenance Technician with HVAC duties (December 2024-October 2025): ~1 year of hands-on HVAC maintenance experience including split units, air handlers, package units, component testing/replacement, and preventive maintenance"]', 'Adrian has approximately 1 year of direct HVAC experience, placing him at 50% of the 2-year requirement (Close to Required tier). His experience is legitimate and well-documented with specific tasks and equipment types. Work history shows NO gaps - he maintained continuous employment through valet work (March 2022-Present) while pursuing his HVAC education and transitioning into the field. He is NOT job hoppy, showing stable employment patterns. The transition from service industry to HVAC is well-executed with educational support. He needs one more year of experience to meet the full requirement, but his trajectory is excellent.', 85, '["Professional formatting with clear sections","Comprehensive detail in HVAC experience section","Well-organized education and certifications","Extensive skills list demonstrating breadth of knowledge","Clean layout with good use of white space","Contact information clearly presented"]', '["Date inconsistency: ''December 2024-October 2025'' appears to be a typo (likely should be 2023-2024 or 2024-Present)","Some redundancy between two different resume formats included","Could consolidate the two versions into one cohesive document","Professional summary could be more concise and achievement-focused"]', 'This is a GOOD quality resume with professional presentation and comprehensive content. The formatting is clean and easy to read with substantive bullets describing actual work performed. The main issue is the date inconsistency which creates confusion about current employment status. The resume appears to contain two versions merged together, which should be consolidated. Minor grammatical improvements could be made, but overall the resume effectively communicates Adrian''s qualifications and career progression.', '["Strong educational foundation with Associate''s degree in HVAC (graduating December 2024)","Complete EPA certification suite (Universal) and Texas state licensing (TDLR)","Hands-on experience with multiple HVAC system types (split, package, rooftop, heat pumps)","Bilingual (English/Spanish) - valuable for diverse customer base","Clean driving record with Class C license - essential for service work","Strong work ethic demonstrated by maintaining multiple jobs while completing education","Comprehensive tool experience including brazing and refrigerant handling"]', '["Only 1 year of HVAC experience vs. 2 years required (50% short of requirement)","Limited customer-facing service experience in HVAC context (mostly maintenance role)","No NATE or manufacturer-specific certifications yet","Date inconsistency on resume creates confusion about current employment status","Experience primarily in maintenance rather than service/repair calls","May need more experience with residential service calls and customer interaction"]', '["Correct the date error on UT Austin position (December 2024-October 2025 is impossible) - likely should be 2023-2024 or 2024-Present","Consolidate the two resume versions into one cohesive document to eliminate redundancy","Pursue NATE Service Technician certification to validate skills and increase marketability","Gain additional 1 year of experience to meet the 2-year requirement - consider service technician roles that provide customer-facing experience","Obtain manufacturer certifications from major brands (Carrier, Trane, Lennox) to expand expertise","Add specific metrics to experience section (e.g., ''Maintained 50+ HVAC units across campus'' or ''Reduced service calls by X%'')","Emphasize customer service skills from valet experience and how they transfer to HVAC service work"]', 'YES', '2025-12-18 00:46:52', '2025-12-18 00:46:52') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (160, 222, 72, 7, 'Ezekiel is a career-changer with excellent foundational HVAC certifications and strong transferable mechanical skills from industrial environments. While he lacks direct HVAC installation experience, his hands-on technical background, leadership experience, safety consciousness, and recent completion of 175-hour HVAC training program make him a promising entry-level candidate who could quickly develop into a productive installer with proper mentorship.', 68, '["Soldering and Brazing Techniques","Refrigerant Recovery and Charging Procedures","Knowledge of Piping Materials and Fittings","Hand and Power Tool Proficiency (grinder, sander, welding equipment)","Problem-Solving and Troubleshooting Skills","High-pressure equipment operation (HydroBlast)","Metal work experience (carbon steel, stainless steel, aluminum)","Quality control and inspection experience","Heavy equipment operation","Working at heights and confined spaces"]', '["HVAC System Installation experience","Ductwork Installation & Fabrication","Residential/Commercial HVAC unit installation","Electrical wiring for HVAC systems","Blueprint/schematic reading for HVAC","System start-up and commissioning","Refrigerant line set installation in field conditions","Sheet metal fabrication","Load calculations","Thermostat installation and programming"]', 'Strong foundational mechanical skills with excellent transferability. His brazing/soldering skills and refrigerant handling knowledge are directly applicable. Metal working experience with various materials demonstrates manual dexterity. However, needs hands-on HVAC-specific installation experience, particularly with ductwork fabrication, electrical connections, and complete system installations. The 175-hour training provides theory but field experience is critical.', 85, '["EPA 608 Universal (essential for refrigerant handling)","TDLR A/C Technician Registration (Texas-specific, excellent)","OSHA-10 Certified (safety foundation)","NATE Ready-to-Work Certification (industry-recognized entry credential)"]', '["NATE Installation Certification (after gaining field experience)","OSHA-30 (for advancement)","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","Electrical/Low-voltage certification","First Aid/CPR","Confined Space Entry certification (refresh/formalize)"]', 'Exceptional certification portfolio for an entry-level candidate. The EPA 608 Universal and TDLR registration are exactly what''s needed. NATE Ready-to-Work shows commitment to the industry. This certification foundation is actually stronger than many entry-level installers and demonstrates serious career transition planning. Once he gains 1-2 years field experience, pursuing full NATE Installation certification would be the logical next step.', 55, 0, '["5+ years industrial equipment operation and maintenance (transferable mechanical aptitude)","Crew leadership and supervision experience (HydroChemPSC - 5 years)","Quality control and inspection background (attention to detail)","Safety-focused work in hazardous environments (refineries, power plants)","Working at heights and confined spaces (scaffolding builder)","High-pressure systems operation (hydroblasting)","Metal fabrication quality inspection","Customer-facing work environments","Physical labor in demanding conditions","Team coordination and training experience"]', 'Zero direct HVAC installation experience is the primary gap, but his industrial background provides strong compensating factors. 15+ years of hands-on mechanical work, including 5 years supervising technical crews, demonstrates capability and reliability. Experience in refineries and power plants shows he can handle complex, safety-critical environments. Physical demands of previous roles (scaffolding, hydroblasting, grinding) prove he can handle the rigors of installation work in attics, crawl spaces, and rooftops. Would be ideal as an installer helper/apprentice with clear path to lead installer within 12-18 months.', 78, '["Clean, professional formatting with clear section headers","Well-organized chronological work history","Specific, quantifiable details (175 hours training, team of four, specific equipment)","Action-oriented bullet points with clear accomplishments","Comprehensive skills section tailored to HVAC transition","Contact information clearly displayed","Good use of industry terminology"]', '["Professional summary emphasizes warehouse/forklift work rather than leading with HVAC transition and mechanical skills","Some redundancy (propane tank refilling listed twice under same job)","Skills section mixes HVAC-specific skills with general equipment (could be better organized)","Missing any hands-on HVAC project examples from training program","Could add a ''Relevant Projects'' section highlighting training capstone work","No mention of physical capabilities (lifting capacity, comfort with heights) which are important for installers","Could strengthen the connection between past mechanical work and HVAC applications"]', 'Solid, professional resume that effectively communicates work history, but could be better optimized for HVAC installer role. The professional summary should lead with ''HVAC Technician with strong industrial mechanical background'' rather than emphasizing warehouse operations. Consider reorganizing skills section into ''HVAC Technical Skills'' and ''Mechanical & Safety Skills'' for better clarity. Add 2-3 bullet points about hands-on projects from the Skillpoint Alliance training to demonstrate practical application of knowledge.', '["Outstanding certification portfolio for entry-level (EPA 608, TDLR, NATE Ready-to-Work, OSHA-10) demonstrates serious commitment to HVAC career","Proven leadership and training ability - supervised 4-person crew for 5+ years, showing potential for future lead installer role","Extensive safety-conscious experience in high-risk industrial environments (refineries, power plants) with perfect implied safety record","Strong mechanical aptitude with hands-on experience in brazing, metal work, high-pressure systems, and quality control","Excellent work history showing reliability and longevity (5+ years at two positions) with progression from operator to supervisor roles","Physical capability proven through demanding roles (scaffolding, hydroblasting, grinding) - can handle attic/crawl space installation work","Recent, relevant training completion (September 2025) means knowledge is fresh and current with modern HVAC practices"]', '["Zero direct HVAC installation experience - has never installed a complete residential or commercial system independently","No demonstrated experience with ductwork fabrication or installation, which is a core installer responsibility","Limited electrical experience - no mention of wiring, circuit work, or low-voltage controls critical for HVAC installations","No blueprint or technical drawing reading experience mentioned - essential for following installation plans and specifications","Lacks manufacturer-specific training on major HVAC brands (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.) that many companies prefer","Resume doesn''t demonstrate customer service in residential settings - industrial B2B experience differs from homeowner interactions","May face learning curve transitioning from industrial pace/environment to residential service timelines and expectations"]', '["Revise professional summary to lead with HVAC focus: ''EPA-certified HVAC Technician with 15+ years mechanical experience in industrial environments, now transitioning to HVAC installation. Combines recent technical training with proven leadership, safety excellence, and hands-on skills in brazing, piping, and equipment operation.''","Add a ''Relevant HVAC Projects'' section highlighting specific installations or labs completed during the 175-hour Skillpoint Alliance training (e.g., ''Installed and charged residential split system,'' ''Fabricated and installed ductwork for commercial application,'' etc.)","Pursue immediate hands-on experience: Apply for installer helper/apprentice positions rather than lead installer roles; consider volunteering with Habitat for Humanity HVAC installations; or seek part-time work with smaller HVAC companies willing to train","Obtain manufacturer certifications: Enroll in free online training from major manufacturers (Carrier University, Trane, Lennox) to add brand-specific credentials and demonstrate initiative","Strengthen electrical knowledge: Take a basic HVAC electrical course or low-voltage certification program to address this critical gap; emphasize any electrical work from training program","Network within local HVAC community: Join local ACCA chapter, attend trade shows, connect with Skillpoint Alliance instructors for job leads and mentorship opportunities in Austin market"]', 'MAYBE', '2025-12-18 00:49:10', '2025-12-18 00:49:10') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO "analyses" ("id", "candidate_id", "overall_score", "score_out_of_10", "summary", "technical_skills_score", "technical_skills_found", "technical_skills_missing", "technical_skills_feedback", "certifications_score", "certifications_found", "certifications_recommended", "certifications_feedback", "experience_score", "years_of_experience", "relevant_experience", "experience_feedback", "presentation_score", "presentation_strengths", "presentation_improvements", "presentation_feedback", "strengths", "weaknesses", "recommendations", "hiring_recommendation", "created_at", "updated_at") VALUES (161, 223, 62, 6, 'Adrian is an emerging HVAC professional with approximately 1 year of hands-on maintenance experience and strong educational credentials (Associate''s in HVAC, EPA certifications). While he demonstrates foundational knowledge in HVAC maintenance and troubleshooting, his experience is heavily weighted toward maintenance rather than installation. His bilingual skills, clean driving record, and willingness to relocate are valuable assets for an installer role.', 58, '["Split system HVAC experience","Package unit familiarity","Air handler knowledge","Capacitor testing and replacement","Contactor testing","Amperage testing","ECM fan motor replacement","Multimeter proficiency","Brazing and oxygen-acetylene experience","Recovery machine operation","Vacuum pump usage","Refrigerant gauge reading","Rooftop work experience","Hand and power tool proficiency","Basic electrical experience","Mechanical troubleshooting"]', '["Ductwork installation and fabrication","Refrigerant line installation (copper piping)","Blueprint/schematic reading","Complete system installation from start to finish","Start-up and commissioning procedures","Load calculations","Residential/commercial new construction installation","Mini-split installation (listed as skill but no demonstrated experience)","Thermostat wiring and programming","Gas line installation and pressure testing"]', 'Adrian has solid maintenance and troubleshooting fundamentals but lacks documented installation-specific experience. His tool experience shows brazing capability, which is essential for installation, but there''s no evidence of actual refrigerant line installation, ductwork fabrication, or complete system installations. For an installer role, he would need significant on-the-job training in installation procedures, though his maintenance background provides a good foundation.', 85, '["EPA 608 Universal Certification (multiple EPA certifications listed: Type I, Type II, Universal)","TDLR License #126947 (Texas HVAC apprentice license)","Associate''s Degree in HVAC and Refrigeration (graduating December 2024)","Clean Class C Driver''s License"]', '["OSHA 10 or OSHA 30 Safety Certification","NATE Installation Certification","Manufacturer-specific certifications (Carrier, Trane, Lennox, etc.)","Refrigeration Service Engineers Society (RSES) certifications","First Aid/CPR certification"]', 'Excellent certification foundation for an entry-level installer. The EPA Universal certification is essential and already obtained. The TDLR apprentice license and Associate''s degree demonstrate commitment to the trade. Adding OSHA safety certification would significantly strengthen his profile for installation work, where safety is paramount. Manufacturer certifications would make him more valuable to specific contractors.', 55, 1, '["1 year as Maintenance Technician at UT Austin (December 2024-October 2025 - NOTE: dates show future employment, likely a typo)","Hands-on experience with split units, air handlers, package units, and window units","Component replacement experience (capacitors, ECM motors, belts)","Rooftop equipment work","Basic electrical testing and diagnostics","Tool proficiency including brazing equipment","Customer interaction through valet service (transferable soft skills)"]', 'Adrian has approximately 1 year of relevant HVAC experience, which meets the minimum threshold for entry-level installer positions. However, his experience is predominantly maintenance-focused rather than installation-focused. The resume shows a concerning date error (December 2024-October 2025 suggests future dates), which needs correction. His non-HVAC work history shows reliability and customer service skills but doesn''t add technical value. For an installer role, he would be best suited for an apprentice or helper position where he can learn installation procedures while leveraging his maintenance knowledge.', 45, '["Comprehensive skills list demonstrates breadth of knowledge","Clear contact information provided","Certifications prominently listed","Bilingual capability highlighted","Tool experience section is detailed and relevant"]', '["Critical date error: UT Austin employment shows December 2024-October 2025 (future dates or reversed dates)","Redundant information - work experience section appears twice with different formatting","Skills section is excessively long and unfocused (80+ skills listed, many irrelevant like ''animal restraint'')","Lacks quantifiable achievements or metrics","Professional summary is too narrative and informal","No clear objective statement for installer position","Inconsistent formatting between sections","Too much emphasis on non-HVAC jobs (valet, delivery, cashier)","Missing key installation-specific accomplishments"]', 'The resume needs significant restructuring for an installer position. The date error is a red flag that must be corrected immediately. The skills section should be condensed to 15-20 highly relevant HVAC installation skills rather than 80+ generic skills. The format is cluttered with duplicate sections and irrelevant information. Adrian should lead with his HVAC experience and education, minimize non-technical jobs to one-line entries, and add specific examples of installations or projects completed during his apprenticeship. A clear objective statement targeting HVAC installation would improve focus.', '["Strong educational foundation with Associate''s degree in HVAC (near completion)","EPA Universal Certification and proper licensing (TDLR) already obtained","Bilingual (English/Spanish) - valuable for diverse customer base and job sites","Hands-on experience with multiple HVAC system types and components","Demonstrated mechanical aptitude across multiple domains (automotive, lawn care, HVAC)","Clean driving record and willingness to relocate shows flexibility","Young and eager to learn with good academic performance (3.1 GPA in technical program)"]', '["Limited installation experience - primarily maintenance and repair focused","No documented experience with ductwork installation or fabrication","Lack of blueprint reading or system design experience mentioned","Resume contains critical date errors that raise credibility concerns","No evidence of complete system installations from start to finish","Missing OSHA safety certification (critical for installation work)","Resume presentation is unfocused with too many irrelevant skills listed","Limited commercial installation experience","No mention of new construction installation experience"]', '["IMMEDIATELY correct the employment date error for UT Austin position (December 2024-October 2025 appears to be future dates or reversed)","Restructure resume to emphasize HVAC experience first - move maintenance technician role to top of experience section and expand with specific installation projects if any exist","Condense skills section from 80+ items to 15-20 core HVAC installation competencies, removing irrelevant skills like ''animal restraint'' and ''grocery store''","Obtain OSHA 10 certification immediately - this is expected for installation work and shows safety consciousness","Add specific, quantifiable achievements (e.g., ''Assisted in installation of 15+ split systems'' or ''Completed 50+ preventive maintenance services'')","Seek additional hands-on installation experience, even if volunteering to assist lead installers on weekends to build installation-specific skills","Create a clear objective statement: ''HVAC Installer seeking entry-level position to apply maintenance expertise and educational training to residential and commercial system installations''","Request manufacturer training or certifications from current or prospective employers (Carrier, Trane, Lennox)","Remove or minimize non-HVAC work history to 1-2 lines each, keeping only customer service and reliability aspects"]', 'MAYBE', '2025-12-18 00:50:04', '2025-12-18 00:50:04') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
